'''Passenger fleet notes'''
[[File:Progress Hong Kong 1a IMG 1286.JPG|thumb|upright|Airbus A330-300 fuselage livery. This aircraft was named "Progress Hong Kong"|alt=Airbus A330-300 with Progress Hong Kong livery]]
On 21 May 1998, Cathay Pacific became the launch carrier when it took the first delivery of the [[Boeing 777-300]], the newest member of the [[Boeing 777]] family, at a ceremony in [[Everett, Washington|Everett]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Boeing and Cathay Pacific Airways Celebrate First 777-300 Delivery|url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/1998/news_release_980521b.html|publisher=[[Boeing]]|date=21 May 1998|accessdate=2009-09-05}}</ref>

On 28 November 2002, the airline took delivery of its first [[Airbus A340-600]] aircraft at a ceremony at the [[Airbus]] factory in [[Toulouse]]. Cathay Pacific is the launch customer in Asia for the A340-600 and this aircraft is the first of three leased from [[International Lease Finance Corporation]] (ILFC).<ref name=A346>{{cite press release|title=Hon Antony Leung tours 1st Cathay Pacific Airbus A340-600|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_INTL/aboutus/pressroomdetails?refID=9a4f22298339a010VgnVCM22000022d21c39____|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=28 November 2002|accessdate=2009-09-05}}</ref>

On 1 December 2005, Cathay Pacific announced an order for 16 [[Boeing 777-300ER]] aircraft, four on lease from ILFC, to be delivered between September 2007 and July 2010, plus [[Option (aircraft purchasing)|options]] on 20 more of the type, two of which were converted to orders on 1 June 2006. The airline also ordered 3 more A330-300 the same day, with the delivery of the aircraft scheduled for 2008.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Boeing Statement on Cathay Pacific Airways 777-300ER Selection|url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/ews/2005/051201g.html|date=1 December 2005|publisher=[[Boeing]]|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Boeing, Cathay Pacific Airways Finalize Agreement for Additional 777-300ERs|url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/2006/q2/060601c_nr.html|date=1 June 2006|publisher=[[Boeing]]|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Cathay Pacific Places Biggest Ever Order For New Aircraft|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_HK/aboutus/pressroomdetails?refID=7f908a88c00ba010VgnVCM22000022d21c39____|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=1 December 2005|accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref>

On 29 August 2006, the airline took delivery of its 100th aircraft, an [[Airbus A330-300]] with the registration B-LAD. For the aircraft acceptance ceremony in Toulouse, the aircraft was painted in a 100th aircraft livery with a 60th anniversary sticker behind the second doors (2L and 2R). The aircraft was named "Progress Hong Kong", a name that was chosen from a competition by the staff.<ref name=100thAC/><ref>{{cite web|title=Cathay Pacific B-LAD Picture of the Airbus A330-343X aircraft|url=http://www.airliners.net/photo/Cathay-Pacific-Airways/Airbus-A330-343X/1107544/L/|publisher=Airliners.net|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref>

On 7 August 2007, Cathay Pacific announced that it had placed an additional order for five more wide-body Boeing 777-300ER aircraft for a total price of about [[US$]]1.4 billion, increasing its commitment to a total of 23 of the aircraft type.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Cathay Pacific Airways Orders Five Additional Boeing 777-300ERs|url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/2007/q3/070807a_nr.html|publisher=[[Boeing]]|date=7 August 2007|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> On 30 October 2007, the airline's [[CEO]], Tony Tyler, stated that the carrier has no plans regarding the purchase of either the [[Boeing 787]] or the [[Airbus A380]] for the time being.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cathay Pacific: no plans for 787 or A380|url=http://www.abcmoney.co.uk/news/302007155134.htm|publisher=ABCmoney. co. uk|date=30 October 2007|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> On 8 November 2007, the airline announced that it had placed an order for seven additional Boeing 777-300ERs and 10 747-8F freighters with a list price of US$5.2 billion.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Boeing and Cathay Pacific Announce Order for 10 747-8Fs and Seven 777-300ERs|url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/2007/q4/071108c_nr.html|publisher=[[Boeing]]|date=8 November 2007|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> In addition, it has also took 14 options for the new freighter at that time. This order, if all options are exercised, would make Cathay Pacific the largest operator of 777-300ERs in Asia and largest operator of 747-8Fs in the world.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cheung|first=Clare|author2=Shen, Irene|title=Cathay Pacific Orders 17 Boeing Jets on China Growth (Update3)|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601089&sid=afRkGr. NJawQ&refer=china|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=8 November 2007|accessdate=2009-07-11}}</ref> On 6 December 2007, the airline placed a firm order for eight more Airbus A330-300 aircraft valued at approximately US$1.7 billion at list prices. Together with the commitment for 17 long-haul passenger aircraft and freighters announced the previous month, the new aircraft will take the Cathay Pacific Group's fleet size to 200 by 2012. From that 200 aircraft, the airline will operate 155 itself, and the rest will be used by its subsidiaries.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Cathay Pacific Group fleet to number 200 in five years with latest aircraft order|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_HK/aboutus/pressroomdetails?refID=6bdd51169eea6110VgnVCM32000011d21c39____|date=6 December 2007|publisher=Cathay Pacific|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref>

On 11 March 2009, it was reported that the delivery of two aircraft due in 2008 was delayed after a strike at [[Boeing]]. Additionally, the delivery of two Boeing 747-8 freighters due this year have been pushed back to 2010 amid delays at the planemaker.<ref name=2008loss/>

The delivery positions on new [[Airbus A330|Airbus A330-300]] and [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777-300ER]] have been deferred due to the [[Late-2000s recession|economic recession]]. Cathay Pacific has also sent four [[Airbus A340|Airbus A340-300]] and two [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-400]] to [[Southern California Logistics Airport|Victorville Airport]] for storage.<ref>http://www.airfleets.net/flottecie/Cathay%20Pacific-stored-a340.htm</ref>

On 8 June 2010, it was reported that Cathay Pacific was in talks with both Boeing and Airbus about adding the [[Boeing 787]] and/or the [[Airbus A350]] to their fleet.  Tony Tyler, Cathay Pacific's CEO, was reported to have said that the airline is more interested in acquiring smaller, long-range jets that are better suited for carrying cargo, than it is in acquiring either the [[Boeing 747-8|Boeing 747-8I]] or the [[Airbus A380]].  Acquisition of the Boeing 787 and/or the Airbus A350 would allow Cathay Pacific to both add new destinations to its network, and to replace those [[Boeing 747|Boeing 747-400s]] and [[Airbus A340|Airbus A340-300s]] that currently operate on its long-haul routes alongside [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777-300ERs]].<ref>http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-07/cathay-pacific-is-in-talks-to-purchase-long-range-jets-shuns-super-jumbos.html</ref>

On 4 August 2010, it was confirmed that Cathay Pacific will buy 30 [[Airbus A350|Airbus A350-900s]] and have 6 more [[Boeing 777|Boeing 777-300ERs]] orders.<ref>{{Cite news | last=Cheng| first=Wing-Gar| title=Cathay Pacific Orders 36 Planes After Profit Beats Expectations| publisher=Bloomberg| date=4/8/10| url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-08-04/cathay-pacific-orders-36-planes-after-profit-beats-expectations.html| accessdate=4 August 2010}}</ref>

===Cargo===
[[File:cathay pacific cargo b747-400bcf b-hkh arp.jpg|thumb|Cathay Pacific Cargo [[Boeing 747-400|Boeing 747-400BCF]] taxis to the runway at [[London Heathrow Airport]]|alt=Cathay Pacific Cargo Boeing 747-400BCF at London Heathrow Airport]]

Cathay Pacific Cargo operates a fleet of 24 freighters to 38 destinations around the world, in addition to utilising the cargo space on its passenger aircraft. The cargo [[subsidiary]] was established in 1981 with a twice-a-week Hong Kong<U+2013>[[Frankfurt]]<U+2013>[[London]] service operated jointly with [[Lufthansa]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cathay Pacific Cargo|url=http://www.cathaypacificcargo.com/usrapps/content/menufooter/menuFooter.aspx?code=aboutus&type=aboutus|publisher=Cathay Pacific Cargo|accessdate=2009-09-02}}</ref> The cargo division ranked fifth in the freight category of the 2008 The World's Top 25 Airlines by [[Air Transport World]].<ref>{{cite news|title=World Airline Report - The World's Top 25 Airlines 2008|work=[[Air Transport World]]|publisher=[[Penton Media]]|date=July 2009|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref>

