'''Cargo fleet notes'''<br />
On 22 June 2006, the airline announced an order of six [[Boeing 747-400ERF]] freighters, delivered in 2008 and 2009.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Major Transaction - Purchase of 6 Boeing 747-400ERF Freighters|url=http://downloads.cathaypacific.com/cx/investor/EW_00293.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=29 June 2006|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref>

On 18 March 2008, [[Airport Authority Hong Kong]] (HKAA) awarded Cathay Pacific Services Ltd (CPSL), a wholly owned subsidiary, a non-exclusive 20-year franchise to invest in, design, construct and operate a new air cargo terminal at [[Hong Kong International Airport]] (HKIA). The new cargo terminal will be built in the cargo area at the airport, close to the existing cargo servicing facilities, with a site area of approximately 10 hectares. The new cargo terminal will be operated by a separate management team in CPSL.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Airport Authority Awards New Cargo Terminal Franchise to Cathay Pacific Services Limited|url=http://www.hongkongairport.com/eng/media/press-releases/pr_920.html|publisher=[[Airport Authority Hong Kong]]|date=18 March 2008|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> On 15 January 2009, CPSL signed a supplementary agreement with the HKAA to defer the completion of its new cargo terminal by a maximum of 24 months to mid-2013, in response to the current market conditions. A non disclosed compensation amount for the deferral is included in the supplementary agreement.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Agreement on deferral of completion of third cargo terminal|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_HK/aboutus/pressroomdetails?refID=a5354d44549de110VgnVCM1000000ad21c39____|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref>

Five [[Boeing 747-400#747-400|Boeing 747-400BCF]] are stored at [[Southern California Logistics Airport|Victorville Airport]] due to [[Late-2000s recession|economic recession]].<ref>http://www.ch-aviation.ch/aircraft.php?search=set&airline=CX&al_op=1</ref>

===Retired===
[[File:CX-DC3-VRHDB2.jpg|thumb|''Betsy''|alt=Cathay Pacific DC-3 ''Betsy'']]
[[File:CPANikki.jpg|thumb|upright|''Niki'' outside Cathay Pacific City|alt=Cathay Pacific DC-3 ''Niki'']]

Since its conception in 1946, the airline had operated many types of aircraft. The first two aircraft were two World War II surplus Douglas DC-3s named ''Betsy'' and ''Niki''. ''Betsy'' (VR-HDB), the first aircraft for Cathay Pacific, is now a permanent exhibit in the [[Hong Kong Science Museum]]. ''Niki'' (VR-HDA) was lost, but a similar DC-3 was purchased as a replacement. It was refurbished and repainted by the airline's Engineering Department and maintenance provider, [[Hong Kong Aircraft Engineering Company]], and it now wears the second Cathay Pacific livery from the late 1940s. This aircraft received ''Niki'''s old VR-HDA aircraft registration and is now on public view in the car park outside the Flight Training Centre of Cathay Pacific City.<ref name=DC3>{{cite press release|title=Vintage Aircraft Brings the Past Alive at Cathay Pacific Headquarter's in Airlines 60th Anniversary Year|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_NZ/aboutus/pressroomdetails?refID=45b8001674c7d010VgnVCM32000011d21c39____|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=5 September 2006|accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref>

Other aircraft that have been in service with Cathay Pacific are (in alphabetical order):

*[[Airbus A340#A340-200|Airbus A340-200]]<ref name=96PastDest/> (leased from [[Philippine Airlines]] for three years before delivery of A340-300)
*[[Airbus A340-600]] (leased from [[ILFC]])
*[[Avro Anson]]
*[[Boeing 707|Boeing 707-320]]
*[[Boeing 747#747-200|Boeing 747-200B]]<ref name=96PastDest>{{cite web|title=The Cathay Pacific Fleet|url=http://web.archive.org/web/19970204081042/cathaypacific.com/our_company/fleet_e.html|publisher=Cathay Pacific|date=October 1996|accessdate=2009-07-23}}</ref> (all retired in 2009)
*[[Boeing 747#747-300|Boeing 747-300]]<ref name=96PastDest/>
*[[Bristol Britannia]] (leased from BOAC for a few months whilst the Electras were taken out of service due to defects)
*[[PBY Catalina|Consolidated PBY Catalina]]<ref name=PBY/>
*[[Convair 880]]<ref name=Convair>{{cite web|title=Accident details - Convair CV-880-22M-3 VR-HFX|url=http://www.planecrashinfo.com/1967/1967-74.htm|publisher=planecrashinfo.com|last=Kebabjian|first=Richard|accessdate=2009-07-02}}</ref>
*[[Douglas DC-3]]<ref name=DC3/>
*[[Douglas DC-4]]<ref name=DC4/>
*[[Douglas DC-6]]
*[[Lockheed L-1011|Lockheed L-1011-100 TriStar]]<ref name=L1011/>
*[[Lockheed L-188 Electra]]

During the late 1980s and early 1990s, Cathay Pacific was the largest operator of the Lockheed TriStar outside the [[United States]].<ref name=L1011>{{cite web|title=FS2004 Lockheed L-1011 TriStar Cathay Pacific Update Package|url=http://www.fsplanet.com/13102005.htm|publisher=fsplanet.com|accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref>

==Loyalty programmes==
Cathay Pacific has two loyalty programmes: The Marco Polo Club (The Club), the loyalty programme, and Asia Miles, the travel reward programme. Members of The Club are automatically enrolled as Asia Miles members.<ref name=MPO>{{cite web|title=The Marco Polo Club|url=http://www.cathayforbusiness.com/freqfly/marcopoloclub.asp|publisher=Cathay Pacific|accessdate=2009-07-03}}</ref> Asia Miles has been named the "Best Frequent Flyer Programme" in the 2009 Business Traveller Asia-Pacific Travel Awards and is the fifth consecutive year it has won the award.<ref>http://downloads.cathaypacific.com/cx/press/SDreport_en2009.pdf</ref> As of April 2010, there were roughly 3.6 million Asia Miles members and 500,000 Marco Polo members.<ref>{{cite web|title=CX World April 2010|url=http://downloads.cathaypacific.com/cx/press/cxw/pdf/CXW169.pdf|publisher=Cathay Pacific|accessdate=2010-04-20}}</ref><onlyinclude><!-- Do Not Remove - use to transclude The Marco Polo Club and Asia Miles sections into Dragonair article -->

===The Marco Polo Club===
[[File:CX Marco Polo Logo.png|thumb|alt=The Marco Polo Club logo|The Marco Polo Club logo]]

The Marco Polo Club is divided into four tiers, Green (entry level), Silver, Gold and Diamond, based on the member's past travel. A joining fee of [[US$]]50 is applicable for a Marco Polo Club membership. Members earn Club Miles and Club Sectors on eligible fare classes with Cathay Pacific, Dragonair and [[Oneworld]] member airlines. These are used to calculate the member's eligibility for membership renewal, upgrade or downgrade during the membership year. Higher-tiered members are provided with increased travel benefits such as guaranteed [[Economy Class]] seat, additional baggage allowance, priority flight booking and airport lounge access. The Marco Polo Club membership is terminated after 12 months of inactivity or failure to meet minimum travel criteria as outlined in the membership guide.<ref name=MPO/><ref name=MPOT&C>{{cite web|title=The Marco Polo Club - Terms and Conditions|url=http://www.cathaypacific.com/cpa/en_HK/ffp/mpo/terms#termination|publisher=Cathay Pacific|accessdate=2009-07-03}}</ref><noinclude><!-- Do Not Remove - use to transclude The Marco Polo Club and Asia Miles sections into Dragonair article -->

<center>
{| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 85%" width="725"
|+ '''The Marco Polo Club Tiers'''
